# Modelfile — fine-tuned Gemma 4 E4B elevator dispatcher (`elevator-gemma`).
# Reference: docs/training-plan.md Stage 5; pre-GPU train==prod checklist.
#
# WHY THERE IS NO HAND-ROLLED TEMPLATE (the train==prod render-identity decision):
# The served base `gemma4:e4b` is google/gemma-4-E4B-it (Q4_K_M; fingerprint- and
# digest-confirmed). Ollama renders it with its BUILT-IN `gemma4` renderer, and the
# base Modelfile's TEMPLATE is the passthrough `{{ .Prompt }}` — the Go renderer,
# not a template string, does all chat formatting.
#
# Gemma 4 also CHANGED its turn delimiters. It does NOT use Gemma-2/3's
# `<start_of_turn>` / `<end_of_turn>` — those strings are NOT tokens in the Gemma-4
# vocab. The real scheme is `<|turn>ROLE\n … <turn|>\n`, turn-ending EOS = `<turn|>`
# (token id 106). A hand-written Go TEMPLATE with the old phantom markers tokenizes
# as raw text and produces broken output (the documented `---`-on-repeat failure of
# mis-templated community Gemma-4 GGUFs).
#
# Therefore the fine-tuned model inherits the SAME formatting path as the validated
# base: passthrough TEMPLATE + `RENDERER gemma4` + `PARSER gemma4`. The LoRA trainer
# formats with the model's own `tokenizer.apply_chat_template` (the official Gemma-4
# template) — so train render == serve render by construction. The render-identity
# gate (tests/test_structural_agent.py::test_chat_template_render_identity) enforces
# this: it fails if this Modelfile reintroduces a divergent template.
#
# Stage-5 build: convert the merged adapter to Q4_K_M GGUF (llama.cpp
# convert_hf_to_gguf.py), then `ollama create elevator-gemma -f Modelfile`. Point
# FROM at that converted GGUF. The full HF-tokenizer-vs-Ollama token-identity check
# runs in the Stage-4 training env (it needs transformers + the exact base
# tokenizer); the offline structural half of the gate runs everywhere.

FROM ./elevator-gemma.Q4_K_M.gguf

# Passthrough template — the gemma4 renderer owns chat formatting (see header).
# Do NOT replace this with a `<start_of_turn>`/`<|turn>` template.
TEMPLATE {{ .Prompt }}
RENDERER gemma4
PARSER gemma4

# Deterministic structured decode — matches the inference path's
# options={"temperature": 0} in policy/structural_agent.py (LLMStructuralProvider).
PARAMETER temperature 0

# num_ctx >= the longest assembled SFT sample. Measured max is ~200 tokens
# (compact get_traffic_summary input + bare {mode,hold} target); 4096 is ample.
PARAMETER num_ctx 4096

# Stopping is owned by `PARSER gemma4`, which ends the turn on `<turn|>` (id 106) —
# exactly the EOS the trainer pins (Unsloth #5386). We deliberately set NO `stop`
# param: a literal "<end_of_turn>" would be a Gemma-2 PHANTOM (absent from the
# Gemma-4 vocab) and re-declaring "<turn|>" is redundant with the parser. This
# mirrors the base gemma4:e4b Modelfile, which sets no stop tokens either.
